% this file tests LaTeX annotations
This brings us to two new formulae. <<<
% here we use a block-level annotation to set the display mode to "inline", which renders all formulae in the block in a single line
#[inline]

f : N x N -> Z
f(a, b) := c
where c := a - b

g : N x N -> Z
g(a, b) := d
where d := a + b
>>> With these, we can define:
<<<
#[box, class="Algorithm", name="My Algorithm Name", label="my_algorithm_name", description="This text provides a description of the algorithm"]

% a hidden formula is not shown in the LaTeX output, but is still available for use in other formulae
@[hidden]
abs : Z -> N
abs(x) := {
    -x if x < 0
    x otherwise
}

% now this formula can use the hidden one
h : N x N -> Q
h(a, b) := e / 6
where e := abs(f(a, b) * g(a, b))
>>>

To give some example values: 
{{{f(1,2)}}}, {{{g(1,2)}}} and {{{h(1,2)}}}.    % here we use evaluation fragments, which will be replaced by the evaluated results of the given expressions

Now, we can finally use Algorithm~\ref{my_algorithm_name} to...

...
<<<
% we can also hide an entire block
% of course these definitions are also still available for reference in other definitions or in evaluation fragments
#[hidden]

id : Z -> Z
id(x) := x

neg : Z -> Z
neg(x) := -abs(x)
>>><<<
#[intext]   % the 'intext' display mode is like inline but with newlines
i : Z -> Z
i(x) := id(x)
>>><<<
% we can have a box with another class to start a fresh counter (counters are made per class)
#[box, class="Procedure", label="doubling"]
k : Z -> Z
k(x) := -2 * neg(y)
where y := i(x)
>>><<<
% or with the same class as before, making the counter automatically increment
#[box, class="Algorithm", name="Another Great Algorithm"]
l : Z -> Z
l(x) := x ^ 2
>>>

Now, using Produce~\ref{doubling} together with this new algorithm, we can evaluate:
{{{l(k(-3))}}}